\description{
\code{fisher_test()} performs Fisher's exact test for independence in a
contingency table. Use this instead of \code{\link{chi_square}()} when your
sample is small or when expected cell frequencies are below 5.

Think of it as:
\itemize{
\item An exact alternative to the chi-square test of independence
\item Best for small samples where the chi-square approximation may be inaccurate
\item SPSS automatically reports Fisher's Exact Test for 2x2 tables
}

The test tells you:
\itemize{
\item Whether two categorical variables are related (exact p-value)
\item The contingency table of observed frequencies
\item Results that are valid even with very small samples
}
}
\details{
\subsection{Understanding the Results}{

\strong{P-value}: If p < 0.05, the variables are likely related (not independent)
\itemize{
\item p < 0.001: Very strong evidence of relationship
\item p < 0.01: Strong evidence of relationship
\item p < 0.05: Moderate evidence of relationship
\item p >= 0.05: No significant relationship found
}

Unlike the chi-square test which uses a large-sample approximation,
Fisher's exact test computes the exact probability of observing the
given table (or a more extreme one) under the null hypothesis of
independence.

For tables larger than 2x2, the Fisher-Freeman-Halton extension is used.
}

\subsection{When to Use This}{

Use Fisher's exact test when:
\itemize{
\item Any expected cell frequency is less than 5
\item Your total sample size is small (typically N < 30)
\item You have a 2x2 table (Fisher's exact is standard here)
\item You want an exact p-value rather than an approximation
}
}

\subsection{Relationship to Other Tests}{
\itemize{
\item For large samples with all expected frequencies >= 5:
Use \code{\link{chi_square}()} instead
\item For paired binary data (before/after):
Use \code{\link{mcnemar_test}()} instead
\item For testing a single proportion:
Use \code{\link{binomial_test}()} instead
}
}

\subsection{SPSS Equivalent}{

SPSS: \code{CROSSTABS /STATISTICS=CHISQ} (Fisher's exact test is
automatically reported for 2x2 tables)
}
